In this article, Vice President Kamala Harris speaks at the Rose Garden about the historic day of celebrating the passage of anti-lynching legislation. She acknowledges the stain on the nation's history and the thousands of people who were tortured and murdered by vigilantes through lynching. Harris highlights that lynching was not considered a federal crime until now, despite numerous attempts to pass legislation over the past century. She praises the efforts of leaders like James Weldon Johnson and Ida B. Wells in advocating for anti-lynching legislation. Harris also mentions her sponsorship of the Emmett Till Antilynching Act with Senator Cory Booker and recognizes the contributions of Senator Tim Scott and Congressman Bobby Rush. She emphasizes that lynching is still a present-day issue and calls for accountability for racial acts of terror. Harris concludes by urging a recommitment to fighting for freedom, opportunity, and justice for all.